ai_contradictions.description: Prostate cancer screening is limited to males over 55 years, which may delay diagnosis in younger high-risk populations.
ai_contradictions.medical_rationale: Clinical guidelines recommend that men at high risk for prostate cancer, including those with a family history or African descent, should begin screening at age 40-45. Restricting screening to those over 55 could lead to missed early-stage diagnoses.
ai_contradictions.patient_safety_risk: Increased risk of late-stage diagnosis and poorer outcomes due to delayed intervention.
ai_contradictions.provider_impact: Confusion regarding eligibility criteria may lead to inconsistent screening practices among providers.
ai_contradictions.evidence: Prostate cancer screening will only be covered in males over 55 years.
ai_contradictions.medical_guidelines: American Urological Association (AUA) guidelines recommend shared decision-making for screening starting at age 40 for high-risk individuals.
ai_contradictions.recommendation: Revise the policy to allow screening for high-risk individuals starting at age 40.

ai_contradictions.description: Emergency services are not available 24/7, which violates standards for critical care access.
ai_contradictions.medical_rationale: Emergency medicine standards dictate that emergency services must be available at all times to ensure timely care for life-threatening conditions. Restricting access to certain hours increases mortality risk.
ai_contradictions.patient_safety_risk: Delayed treatment for emergencies can lead to preventable morbidity and mortality.
ai_contradictions.provider_impact: Providers may face challenges in delivering timely care, leading to increased liability and stress.
ai_contradictions.evidence: Emergency services must be available 24/7 with appropriate triage and resuscitation capabilities.
ai_contradictions.medical_guidelines: American College of Emergency Physicians (ACEP) guidelines emphasize the need for 24/7 emergency services.
ai_contradictions.recommendation: Ensure all emergency facilities are staffed and equipped to provide care 24/7.

ai_contradictions.description: Complex surgical procedures are being performed at Level 3 facilities, which lack the necessary infrastructure.
ai_contradictions.medical_rationale: Surgical safety standards require that complex procedures be performed in facilities equipped with appropriate surgical support and emergency backup. Level 3 facilities may not have the necessary resources.
ai_contradictions.patient_safety_risk: Increased risk of surgical complications and inadequate postoperative care.
ai_contradictions.provider_impact: Surgeons may face ethical dilemmas and increased stress due to inadequate facilities.
ai_contradictions.evidence: Complex surgical procedures require appropriate facility infrastructure and specialist availability.
ai_contradictions.medical_guidelines: American College of Surgeons (ACS) guidelines recommend that complex surgeries be performed in facilities with the necessary resources.
ai_contradictions.recommendation: Restrict complex surgical procedures to Level 4 and above facilities.

ai_contradictions.description: Pediatric care protocols are not clearly defined, leading to potential gaps in treatment for children.
ai_contradictions.medical_rationale: Pediatric care requires specific protocols that differ from adult care due to physiological differences. Lack of clear guidelines can lead to inappropriate treatment.
ai_contradictions.patient_safety_risk: Increased risk of misdiagnosis or inappropriate treatment in pediatric patients.
ai_contradictions.provider_impact: Providers may be uncertain about the appropriate care pathways for pediatric patients.
ai_contradictions.evidence: Pediatric care services lack specific guidelines and protocols.
ai_contradictions.medical_guidelines: American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) guidelines emphasize the need for age-appropriate care protocols.
ai_contradictions.recommendation: Develop and implement clear pediatric care protocols in line with AAP guidelines.

ai_contradictions.description: Mental health services require pre-authorization, which may delay necessary care.
ai_contradictions.medical_rationale: Timely access to mental health services is critical for effective treatment. Requiring pre-authorization can create barriers to care and worsen patient outcomes.
ai_contradictions.patient_safety_risk: Delays in accessing mental health care can lead to worsening of conditions and increased risk of crises.
ai_contradictions.provider_impact: Providers may face challenges in delivering timely care, leading to frustration and potential burnout.
ai_contradictions.evidence: Mental illness services will be assessed through the SHIF and ECCI funds.
ai_contradictions.medical_guidelines: National Institute of Mental Health (NIMH) emphasizes the importance of timely access to mental health services.
ai_contradictions.recommendation: Eliminate pre-authorization requirements for mental health services to improve access.
